# UI test patterns

## Architecture

UI tests use a **three-layer structure**:

| Layer | Location | Responsibility |
|-------|----------|----------------|
| **Spec** | `tests/ui-tests/*.spec.ts` | Test logic only; uses `PageManager`, never page objects directly |
| **PageManager** | `page-objects/pageManager.ts` | Single entry point: exposes `navigateTo()`, `auth()`, `article()` so specs stay DRY |
| **Page objects** | `page-objects/navigationPage.ts`, `authPage.ts`, `articlePage.ts` | One class per area; extend `HelperBase`; methods = user actions, locators KISS in methods |
| **HelperBase** | `page-objects/helperBase.ts` | Base class: holds `page`, shared helpers (e.g. `waitForNumberOfSeconds`) |

**Structure:**

```
page-objects/
  helperBase.ts      — base class (page, shared helpers)
  pageManager.ts     — facade: new PageManager(page) → navigateTo(), auth(), article()
  navigationPage.ts — extends HelperBase: gotoHome(), loginPage(), signUpPage(), newArticlePage()
  authPage.ts       — extends HelperBase: login()
  articlePage.ts    — extends HelperBase: createNewArticle(), deleteArticle()
tests/ui-tests/
  smokeUItest.spec.ts, *.spec.ts — import { PageManager }; use pm.navigateTo().gotoHome(), pm.auth().login(), etc.
```

**Spec usage:** One instance of `PageManager(page)` per test; access page objects only via `pageManager.navigateTo()`, `pageManager.auth()`, `pageManager.article()`.

## Page Object Model

Page objects live in `page-objects/`. Each extends `HelperBase`. Use **named exports** (`export class X`).

### Page object template

Locators **KISS in methods** (no class-level `Locator` properties). Extend `HelperBase` for shared `page` and helpers:

```ts
import { Page } from "@playwright/test";
import { HelperBase } from "./helperBase";

export class NavigationPage extends HelperBase {
  constructor(page: Page) {
    super(page);
  }

  async gotoHome() {
    await this.page.goto("/");
  }

  async loginPage() {
    await this.page.getByRole("link", { name: "Sign in" }).click();
  }
}
```

### Page object rules

- **Locators KISS in methods** — define selectors inside the method that uses them; no `Locator` properties on the class. Keeps selector and action together, avoids duplication.
- **Methods encapsulate actions** — one method = one user action or step. Tests call methods, not raw locators.
- **No assertions in page objects** — assertions stay in specs. Page objects only interact.
- **Use `getByRole`, `getByLabel`, `getByText`** for locators — prefer semantic selectors over CSS/XPath.

## UI spec template

Specs use **PageManager** only; no direct imports of page objects.

```ts
import { test, expect } from "@playwright/test";
import { PageManager } from "../../page-objects/pageManager";

test("user can sign in and create article", async ({ page }) => {
  const pm = new PageManager(page);
  await pm.navigateTo().gotoHome();
  await pm.navigateTo().loginPage();
  await pm.auth().login(email, password);
  await expect(page.getByRole("link", { name: "New Article" })).toBeVisible();
});
```

## API-assisted UI tests

For tests that need data already in the system (e.g. an article to view), use Playwright's `request` fixture in `beforeEach` or `test.beforeAll` to set up state via the API — do not drive the UI just to create prerequisites.

```ts
test.beforeEach(async ({ request }) => {
  // create article via API so UI test can find it
  await request.post("https://conduit-api.bondaracademy.com/api/articles", {
    headers: { Authorization: authToken },
    data: { article: { title: "...", description: "...", body: "..." } },
  });
});
```

Or reuse `createToken` and `RequestHandler` directly for full framework consistency.

## Locator strategy — preference order

1. `getByRole` — most resilient to UI changes
2. `getByLabel` — for form fields
3. `getByText` — for visible text
4. `getByTestId` — if `data-testid` attributes are added
5. CSS selector — last resort

## Config

UI base URL comes from `playwright.config.ts` → `use.baseURL` (set from `config.ui.baseURL`). Use relative paths in `page.goto()`:

```ts
await page.goto("/"); // https://conduit.bondaracademy.com/
await page.goto("/login"); // https://conduit.bondaracademy.com/login
```

## Run UI tests

Use npm scripts (see `package.json`):

| Command                    | What it does                                              |
| -------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| `npm run ui-test`          | Run UI tests (browser opens by default)                   |
| `npm run ui-test:debug`    | Run with Playwright Inspector — step through, time travel |
| `npm run ui-test:headless` | Run without opening the browser                           |
| `npm run ui-test:slow`     | Run with 500ms delay between actions (watch what happens) |

Or run Playwright directly:

```bash
npx playwright test --project=ui-testing          # uses config (headed for UI)
npx playwright test --project=ui-testing --debug   # step through with inspector
```

## Record UI tests

Specs can be **recorded** with Playwright codegen, then refactored and the recorded file removed:

```bash
npx playwright codegen --target=javascript https://conduit.bondaracademy.com -o tests/ui-tests/recorded.spec.ts
```

**Workflow:** After recording, review the generated code, transform it into a proper test (use page objects, semantic locators like `getByRole`/`getByLabel`, config for credentials/URLs). Move or merge the test into the right spec file, then **remove** `recorded.spec.ts` so it does not stay in the repo.

## Keep browser open

- **Debug run** — `npm run ui-test:debug` opens the Playwright Inspector; the browser stays open and you step through each action (Step, Pause, Resume). Execution only continues when you click Step/Resume.
- **Pause in code** — Add `await page.pause()` where you want execution to stop. Run any UI test (e.g. `npm run ui-test`); when that line runs, the Inspector opens and the browser stays open until you resume or close.

## Step-by-step execution (like VS Code)

- **In Cursor/VS Code (recommended):** Install the **Playwright Test for VS Code** extension. Open a spec, click **"Debug Test"** above a `test(...)` or `test.describe(...)`. You get the normal debugger: set breakpoints (click gutter), F10 step over, F11 step into, watch variables — same as debugging any other code.
- **From terminal:** `npm run ui-test:debug` opens the **Playwright Inspector** (separate window). Use "Step" to run one action at a time; the browser and Inspector stay open until you resume or close.
